natural problem: One of the roots of $z^2 = -55 + 48i$ is $3 + 8i.$  What is the other root?
natural solution: The other root is simply the negative of $3 + 8i,$ which is $\boxed{-3 - 8i}.$

a_0.formal problem:
theorem
fixes z :: complex
assumes h0 : "z\<^sup>2 = Complex (Re (-55)) (Im 48)"
and h1 : "z = Complex (Re 3) (Im 8)"
shows  "conj z = Complex (Re (-3)) (Im (-8))"
a_0.formal solution:

 *)

theorem
fixes z :: complex

  show ?thesis sledgehammer
